Therefore, pairs of consecutive terms cannot form a fragrant set. 2. **Checking triples**: - We need to find three terms where each pair shares a common divisor greater than 1. - Consider the terms \( P(1) = 3 \), \( P(4) = 21 \), and \( P(7) = 57 \). These terms are all multiples of 3: - \( \gcd(3, 21) = 3 \) - \( \gcd(3, 57) = 3 \) - \( \gcd(21, 57) = 3 \) - Each pair shares a common factor of 3, making the set \(\{3, 21, 57\}\) fragrant. 3. **Verification**: - The set \(\{3, 21, 57\}\) is verified to be fragrant as each element is not coprime to the product of the other elements. Thus, the smallest size of a fragrant set is \(\boxed{3}\).
